         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ [From a letter received from Dr Mueller, the highly reputed director of the Melbourne botanical garden in Australia, we learn that he has worked around the Chenopodiaceae to ascertain the need to b...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">70.06.00b</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="de">To Théodore Caruel</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Letter not found. The text given here is from '<seg style="">L</seg>avori del Dr Mueller sulle Chenopodiacee' [Dr. Mueller's works on Chenopodiaceae], <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Nuovo giornale botanico italiano</seg>
                     <seg style="">, vol. 2 (1870), p. 314. It is dated to June 1870 as the earliest date that it could have been sent after M had received proof sheets of the treatment of Chenopodiaceae in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 5, announced as sent in G. Bentham to M, 15 April 1870, and receipt acknowledged in M to G. Bentham, 17 June 1870, in which M comments on Bentham's treatment of </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Chenopodium">Chenopodium</name>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style=""> and </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Blitum</seg>
                     <seg style="">, mentioned in the text.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[Da lettera avuta dal Dr Mueller, il riputatissimo direttore del giardino botanico di Melbourne in Australia, apprendiamo che egli lavorando attorno alle Chenopodiacee si è accertato della necessità di riunire il genere </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Blitum</seg>
               <seg style=""> ai </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Chenopodium">Chenopodium</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">, come pure di mettere le specie nord-americane e asiatiche di </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Monolepis">Monolepis</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> nel genere </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Dysphania">Dysphania</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">, che perciò contiene ora 5 specie; già fin dal 1858 il chiarissimo botanico aveva unito gli </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Obione">Obione</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> agli </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Atriplex">Atriplex</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">; propone pure di unire </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Hemichroa">Hemichroa</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> e </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Polycnemum">Polycnemum</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">, e approva la riunione fatta dal sig. Bentham nella Flora Australiana di </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Echinopsilon">Echinopsilon</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> e </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Chenolea">Chenolea</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">, cosicchè la </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Kochia%20hirsuta">Kochia hirsuta</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> di Europa diventerebbe ora una </seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Chenolea">Chenolea</name>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">.]</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; line-height: 0.1945in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[From a letter received from Dr Mueller, the highly reputed director of the Melbourne botanical garden in Australia, we learn that he has worked around the Chenopodiaceae to ascertain the need to bring together the genus <name key="Blitum%20">Blitum </name>with <name key="Chenopodium">Chenopodium</name>, as well as to put the North American and Asian species of <name key="Monolepis">Monolepis</name> in the genus <name key="Dysphania">Dysphania</name>, which therefore now contains 5 species; already by the end of 1858 the illustrious botanist had combined <name key="Obione">Obione</name> with <name key="Atriplex">Atriplex</name>; he also proposes to unite <name key="Hemichroa">Hemichroa</name> and <name key="Polycnemum">Polycnemum</name>, and approves the unification made by Mr. Bentham in the Australian Flora of <name key="Echinopsilon">Echinopsilon</name> and <name key="Chenolea">Chenolea</name>, so that the <name key="Kochia%20hirsuta">Kochia hirsuta</name> of Europe would now become a <name key="Chenolea">Chenolea</name>.<seg style=""> </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M worked up this group, as Salsolaceae, in B69.06.03, pp. 8-15. He united <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Blitum</seg> with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Chenopodium">Chenopodium</name>
                     </seg> in his treatment of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. cristatum</seg> and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. atriplicinum</seg> on p. 11; he did not mention <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Monolepis">Monolepis</name>
                     </seg> in his treatment of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Dysphania">Dysphania</name>
                     </seg> (p. 11); he maintained <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Echinopsilon">Echinopsilon</name>
                     </seg> on p. 13, but it was united with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Chenolea">Chenolea</name>
                     </seg> by Bentham (1863-78), vol. 5, p 189. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Obione">Obione</name>
                     </seg> was not mentioned in his treatment of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Atriplex">Atriplex</name>
                     </seg>, pp. 8-10. In B57.09.04, pp. 74-5 he had however listed '(<name key="Obione">Obione</name>)' under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Atriplex">Atriplex</name> leptocarpum</seg>, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">A. spongiosum</seg> and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">A. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>inflatum</seg>, possibly indicating that he considered these three species to be in the <name key="Obione">Obione</name> section of the genus. That view is consistent with his usage when listing Babbage's collection, in B59.03.01, where for example he uses <seg style="font-style: italic; ">'<name key="Atriplex">Atriplex</name> incrassatum</seg> (Sect. <name key="Obione">Obione</name>.)' (p. 20). M united <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Polycnemum">Polycnemum</name>
                     </seg> with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Hemichroa">Hemichroa</name>
                     </seg> in his treatment of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">H. mesembryanthema</seg> in B73.04.02, p. 38.</p>
               </note>]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
